                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SPORT BRIEFS
                                                                Carl Lewis on audit panel	  Indianapolis: Carl Lewis, winner of nine Olympic gold medals, has been selected member of USA Track and Field rsquo;s seven-member audit panel, chief executive Doug Logan announced on his blog.  The committee will analyse the selection process for the team, coaching and preparation for international competitions. Members will also study the performance of the Beijing team, in particular the national relay team rsquo;s preparation and training.   Crowd trouble  Madrid: Uefa has ordered Spanish club Atletico Madrid to play their next two Champions League home matches at least 300 kilometres away from Madrid following crowd trouble earlier this month against Olympique Marseille.  Suspects held   London: Two housekeepers working at a mansion owned by former England football captain David Beckham and his pop star wife Victoria have been arrested on suspicion of theft, reports said Tuesday.   Simi leads   Chandigarh: Simi Mehra brought home the lone sub-par card of the day to open up a massive seven-shot lead over Nalini Singh in the fourth leg of DLF Women's Professional Golf Tour here on Tuesday. The US-based Indian reeled off five birdies against three bogeys for an impressive opening round.   Pujara shines   Rajkot: Promising middle order batsman, Cheteshwar Pujara celebrated his inclusion in challenger trophy by cracking a triple century against visitors Maharashtra in the CK Naidu Trophy. The match ended in draw here on Monday.   Put into bat first, Maharashtra rode on S. Ajitkar rsquo;s 120-run knock and A. Joshi rsquo;s unbeaten 89 to score 368. In reply, Saurashtra piled up 546/8. Pujara played a marathon innings, spending 696 minutes at the crease, scoring 386.   Brief scores: Maharashtra 368 amp; 50/2 vs Saurashtra 546/8 decl. (C. Pujara 386, R. Jadeja 72).   Panesar plans   London: Monty Panesar will warm up for England rsquo;s Test series in India by playing club cricket in Sri Lanka, coach Peter Moores said on Tuesday.   Lanka win   Toronto: Sanath Jayasuriya and Ajantha Mendis led Sri Lanka to a five-wicket victory over Pakistan in the Canada Twenty20 final here.   Brief scores: Pakistan 132/7 in 20 overs (S. Butt 44, A. Mendis 3/23) lost to Sri Lanka 133/5 in 19 overs (S. Jayasuriya 40, S. Malik 2/17)
                                                                                                                                                                 
